        {
          "id": "WDrthInYqdsEXLjT",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>Students have to think about how many pizzas make sense for an extra-large table. Then they have to figure out what to do with the fact that at least one table will not be full, since 25 is not a factor of 210.</p><ul><li>How many pizzas make sense for the extra-large table? (Answers will vary. Possible reasoning may include: 25 is about 3 times 8, so there could be 3 x 3 or 9 pizzas at an extra-large table. Or 25 is 2.5 times 10, so there could be 2.5 x 4 or 10 pizzas at an extra-large table. Or somewhere between 3/8 and 4/10 of a pizza per person. Or just use the amount on the large table because that had the most pizza for each person.)</li><li>What strategies did you use to find the number of pizzas? (Answers will vary. Possible answers may include proportions, equivalent ratios, or scaling up.)</li></ul>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "TILEgmoGsubqwiID",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u>Now What Do Students Know</u></p><p>Ask students to reflect on the discussion and answer the Now What Do You Know.</p><p>Students used proportions in Investigation 1, but probably not in this Problem. They may have compared ratios or scaled up or down. Investigation 1 had part to part and part to whole comparisons. Problem 2.1 is all part-to-part ratios.</p><p>See answers for more information about the strategies and embedded mathematics.</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "GwC8YVmuD9_HbVMS",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Reflecting on Student Learning</strong></p><p>Use the following questions to assess student understanding at the end of the lesson.</p><ul><li>What evidence do I have that students understand the Now What Do You Know?</li></ul><ol><li>Where did my students get stuck?</li><li>What strategies did they use?</li><li>What breakthroughs did my students have today?</li></ol><ul><li>How will I use this to plan for tomorrow? For the next time I teach this lesson?</li><li>Where will I have the opportunity to reinforce these ideas as I continue through this Unit? The next Unit?</li></ul>"
            ]
          }
        }
