  "cas/teacher-guide/investigation-2/problem-3/explore/content.json": {
    "type": "explore",
    "content": {
      "tiles": [
        {
          "id": "9vggRGaUkA3LPVYy",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u><strong>Explore (Digging In</strong></u>)</p><p><u>Providing for Individual Needs</u></p><p>As groups work on this Problem, make sure that students are relating the two quantities in the rate table to the variables in the equations and graphs.</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "WV8OKLgHJmAo_mdw",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Suggested Questions:</strong></p><ul><li>What does the <em>N</em> stand for in the equations? (number of oranges)</li><li>Where do you see number of oranges in the table? (top row) In the graph? (In one graph it is the dependent variable. In the other graph it is the independent variable.)</li><li>What does the <em>C </em>stand for in the equations? (total cost in dollars)</li><li>Where do you see total cost in dollars in the table? (bottom row) In the graph? (In one graph it is the dependent variable. In the other graph it is the independent variable.)</li><li>In What if...? Situation A, what does the table, graph, or equation say to you? (Answers will vary. Get students to discuss how each relates to Noralie buying tickets for the concert.)</li><li>For What if...? Situation B, is there a previous strategy that could help you? (Answers will vary. Students may suggest a table, graph, unit rate, equation, scaling, etc.)</li></ul>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "TILEWrJGhAK3XLkj",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u>Planning for the Summary</u></p><p>What evidence will you use in the Summary to clarify and deepen understanding of the Now What Do You Know? What will you do if you do not have evidence?</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "d-tu-6qCU9CXdlby",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><em>Now What Do You Know?</em></p><p><em>Describe how you can determine a unit rate, or constant of proportionality, in a description, rate table, equation, or graph. In what ways is a unit rate or the constant of proportionality helpful for solving a problem? Select student work for each representation to discuss how they found the unit rate or the constant of proportionality.</em></p><p>(Select student work for each representation to discuss how they found the unit rate or constant of proportionality.)</p>"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "cas/teacher-guide/investigation-2/problem-3/launch/content.json": {
    "type": "launch",
    "content": {
      "tiles": [
        {
          "id": "pXrpNiK6YKAmqCnP",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u><strong>Problem Overview</strong></u></p><p>This problem focuses on how unit rate, or constant of proportionality, is helpful to solve problems. Students also look at the role of unit rate in different representations of tables, graphs, and equations.  Students began their study of multiplicative relationships in the grade 6 unit <em>Number Connections.</em></p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "Ce0ddFqDIekcTc0W",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u><strong>Launch (Getting Started)</strong></u></p><p><u>Connecting to Prior Knowledge</u></p><p>If you did not introduce the vocabulary of <strong>constant of proportionality </strong>in the Ssummary of Problem 2.2, you can introduce the term now. Since the quantities for Royal Pizza are proportional, the constant of proportionality is 13. Since the quantities for Howdy’s Pizza are not proportional, there is no constant of proportionality.</p><p>If we let <em>C</em> represent the cost of a pizza and <em>N</em> represent the number of pizzas,</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "aOBBfjAILB8J9wsO",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><em>Royal Pizza</em></p><p>With the proportional situation, both equations are equivalent. You can multiply one variable by a constant number to get the value of the other variable.</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        [
          {
            "id": "kUu7QKoYHGFm8LGF",
            "title": "Proportion Equation",
            "content": {
              "type": "Expression",
              "latexStr": "\\frac{C}{N}=\\frac{13}{1}"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "0tQXbmu2HIBbQNfs",
            "title": "Linear Equation",
            "content": {
              "type": "Expression",
              "latexStr": "C=13N"
            }
          }
        ],
        {
          "id": "VLndSuMeVRsGUjqc",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><em>Howdy’s Pizza</em></p><p>Linear Equation: C = 11N + 30</p><p>You cannot write C = 11N + 30 as a proportion. The add-on changes the unit rate with each N. So there is no constant of proportionality. You cannot multiply one variable by a constant number to get the value of the other variable.</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "zUaaoxdPbicBpQ-C",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Note:  </strong>The unit rate, 5/65 pizza for $1, exists but it might not be as useful depending on the situation.</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "getpqErblcxAR-Dn",
          "title": "Unit Rate",
          "content": {
            "type": "Expression",
            "latexStr": "\\frac{5pizzas}{65dollars}=\\frac{\\left(\\frac{5}{65}\\right)}{1dollar}"
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "F77Bc8AeJUqG1cOM",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><u>Presenting the Challenge</u></p><p>Students will be analyzing the proportionality in descriptions, tables, graphs, and equations.  Let students know that the situation involves a sale on oranges where they are 10 oranges for $2.  Students will analyze how they can use this information to think about buying any number of oranges. Have students begin this work independently for a few minutes and then work with a partner.</p>"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
