  "brain/investigation-1/problem-1/intro/content.json": {
    "type": "intro",
    "content": {
      "tiles": [
        {
          "id": "zyoT6wp_c7IxjDmS",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Overview: </strong></p><p>Throughout this unit, we will explore how bionic arms work. Bionic arms are designed for people with limb differences (e.g., people who lost a limb as a result of an accident). With recent developments in science and engineering, these individuals can now directly control a prosthetic arm as if it was their own biological arm. Throughout the unit, you will also learn about the engineering design process: what do engineers do and how their work can help people.</p><p><strong>Learning Objectives: </strong></p><p>This activity is intended to help you come up with questions about how body systems interact with one another and with technology. </p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "bj5dqEB0okmYf9qy",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>To start off, please drag the following tile into your workspace and answer these questions:</p><p>1) What do you know about bionic arms? (e.g., what they look like, why people might use them, in what ways are they connected to the person’s body, how they work)</p><p>2) If you were tasked to design a bionic arm, what do you think the people who use them would like in terms of appearance and function?</p>"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "brain/investigation-1/problem-1/labWork/content.json": {
    "type": "labWork",
    "content": {
      "tiles": [
        {
          "id": "EqKYUNT3JvLoOuzP",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Meet Tilly</strong></p><p>Tilly is a real-life bionic teen.  At only 15 months old, Tilly had both of her hands amputated at the wrist because of a very rare infection. For years she used basic silicon arms, but in 2018 she became the first child in the UK to have bionic arms. These high-tech, 3D printed arms give Tilly a much fuller range of movement. In class, you will watch a video about Tilly,  who is now a model, public speaker and make-up vlogger. In the video, Tilly showcases her colorful arm cases, before applying a full face of make-up - and trying out a new look. </p><p>This <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q2MjTcmLuIQ\">video</a> has over 2.2M views on YouTube! <a href=\"https://openbionics.com/bionic-tilly/\"></a></p><p>While watching the video, think about how Tilly controls her bionic arm. </p><p>After watching the video, write down as many questions as possible on the sticky notes your teacher gives you. These will form a Driving Question board for you to refer to at any time through this unit. </p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "ULWVknRyAIhw-jUC",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>How does Tilly control her bionic arms?</strong></p><p>Drag the following tile into your workspace and answer the question:</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "GaWlzxAIiVRieZlp",
          "title": "Text 1",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>What challenges might come up if you were using bionic arms?</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "t3Ibad3vX7gtfBsk",
          "title": "Text 3",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>Now, choose one challenge you came up with and think how to address it. This is the first step of the engineering design process. This step is called a “Need Statement.” Your statement should be in the following format (drag and drop the following prompt into your workspace and revise it): </p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "h4t2bHsZE1GlU6xC",
          "title": "Text 4",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>“People using a bionic arm need X in order to do Y.”</p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "UF4zbIK9h5t1i1-R",
          "title": "Text 2",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p><strong>Creating a diagram or a flowchart</strong></p><p>Next, let’s dive deeper into how bionic arms work. </p><p>Create a diagram or a flowchart that explains how you think Tilly is controlling her bionic arms. </p><p>You can create the diagram or flowchart on paper or a whiteboard, or in a ‘Sketch’ drawing tile here in CLUE. </p><p>Be sure to add anything you think is important to how Tilly controls the bionic arms.</p><p>Think about  how the bionic arm is connected to Tilly’s body and what Tilly needs to do to make the bionic arm move. </p><p>If you worked on paper or a whiteboard, take a picture of your work  and upload it to your workspace in an ‘Image’ tile. </p><p>To help you develop the model, you can read more about Tilly and her bionic arms  <a href=\"https://openbionics.com/bionic-tilly/\">here</a> .</p><p><strong>Reflection</strong></p><p>At the end of the activity, please record your current thinking and learning in your Learning journal (see Reflection tab). </p>"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
